{"title_page": "Bougainvillia aberrans", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n| taxon = Bougainvillia aberrans\n| authority = Calder, 1993\n}}\n\n'''''Bougainvillia aberrans''''' is a marine [[invertebrate]], a [[species]] of [[hydroid (zoology)|hydroid]] in the suborder [[Anthomedusae]].<ref name=\":0\">Calder, D. R. (1993). Bougainvillia aberrans (Cnidaria, Hydrozoa), a new species of hydroid and medusa from the upper bathyal zone off Bermuda. ''Canadian Journal of Zoology'', ''71''(5), 997\u20131002. doi: 10.1139/z93-132</ref> It was first described by Dale Calder in 1993.<ref>{{cite WoRMS |author=Peter Schuchert |year=2010 |title=''Bougainvillia aberrans'' Calder, 1993 |db=Hydrozoa |id=284227 |accessdate=June 26, 2012}}</ref> They have four radical clusters of marginal [[Tentacle|tentacles]]. <ref>''Bougainvillia Sp. - Guide to the Marine Zooplankton of South Eastern Australia'', web.archive.org/web/20120322022902/http:/www.tafi.org.au/zooplankton/imagekey/cnidaria/hydrozoa/hydroidomedusae/anthomedusae/bougainvillia.html.</ref> ''Bougainvillia aberrans'' is found in [[Bermuda]] in the western [[North Atlantic Ocean]]. <ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Description ==\n''Bougainvillia aberrans'' consists of the [[hydroid]] colony with soft curly [[perisarc]] polysiphonic hydrocaulus, hydranths <ref name=\":0\" /> including 16 tentacles maximum, and medusa buds. Hydroid is part of the Cnidaria phylum. <ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=Castro, Peter,|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/1085562213|title=Marine biology|others=Huber, Michael E.,, Ober, William C.,, Ober, Claire E.,|isbn=1-260-08510-4|edition=Eleventh edition|location=New York, NY|oclc=1085562213}}</ref> So, ''B. aberrans'' are radial symmetry, that they have [[Cnidaria|cnidae]] that are unique sting structures unique to this phylum. <ref name=\":2\" /> ''Bougainvillia aberrans'' is different from other [[Hydrant|hydranths]] species because ''B. abberans'' have a lengthy spindled manubrium, negligible tentacles, and survive for a short period. In the sense that different from other with known species in all. <ref name=\":0\" />This species is characterized as comparatively large size, about 20 mm width as well as height, and large amounts of folded hanging [[Gonad|gonads]] from the wall around the circumference to the proximal area of the radial canals. <ref name=\":1\" /> Also, The edge tentacles have extinct species, and the oral tentacles have anti-inflammatory properties. <ref name=\":1\">Nogueira, M., Rodriguez, C. S., Mianzan, H., Haddad, M. A., & Genzano, G. (2013). Description of a new hydromedusa from the southwestern Atlantic Ocean,Bougainvillia pagesisp. nov. (Cnidaria, Hydrozoa, Anthoathecata). ''Marine Ecology'', ''34'', 113\u2013122. doi: 10.1111/maec.12030</ref> \n\n<br />\n\n== Distribution and habitat ==\nHydroid species ''Bougainvillia aberrans'' distribute from shallow water to deep sea in the Bermuda area. <ref>Calder, D. R. (1998). Hydroid diversity and species composition along a gradient from shallow waters to deep sea around Bermuda. ''Deep Sea Research Part I: Oceanographic Research Papers'', ''45''(11), 1843\u20131860. doi: 10.1016/s0967-0637(98)00044-2</ref> Members of the genus are found in all seas, but most of the known species are found in the [[Atlantic Ocean]]. In the western [[North Atlantic ocean|North Atlantic Ocean]], southeast of Castle Roads, this species was collected with a depth of 300 meters. <ref name=\":0\" />\n<br />\n\n== Biology ==\nHydroid colonies arise or stand upright due to creeping hydrorhiza .Monosiphonic or polysiphonic hydrocaulus are companions of erect colonies. <ref name=\":0\" /> ''Bougainvillia aberrans'' is distinguishable in the sense that the degree of reduction of its medusa is unique compared to species of same genus. Moreover, ''B. aberrans'' is suppressed in the medusa stage. Hydroids of ''B. aberrans'' feed on fragments of other cnidarians. <ref name=\":2\" /> Cnidaria have a centered mouth surrounded by tentacles. Also, the they are carnivorous. <ref name=\":2\" /> In terms of reproduction, gametes were released before or shortly after the release of the mediating from the hydroid. ''Bougainvillia aberrans n. sp''. has [[holotype]] and [[paratype]]. Also, medusae ''of B. aberrans'' appear sexually mature and relatively short-lived for release from the hydroid. It is different from the reduced Medusa buds with its blunt marginal tentacles. Furthermore, the perisarc of ''B. aberrans'' is clear and not covered with mud or sand. The latest ''B. aberrans'' eggs are surrounded by envelopes with tiny heterotrchous microbasic eurytele [[Nematocyst (dinoflagellate)|nematocysts]]. <ref name=\":0\" /> The exoskeleton of Hydroid and Bougainvillidae family starts as epidermal secretions. <ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Mendoza-Becerril|first=Mar\u00eda A.|last2=Marian|first2=Jos\u00e9 Eduardo A.R.|last3=Migotto|first3=Alvaro Esteves|last4=Marques|first4=Antonio Carlos|date=2017-02-16|title=Exoskeletons of Bougainvilliidae and other Hydroidolina (Cnidaria, Hydrozoa): structure and composition|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5316283/|journal=PeerJ|volume=5|doi=10.7717/peerj.2964|issn=2167-8359|pmc=5316283|pmid=28224050}}</ref> Coenosarc, which is the epithelial epidermal layer consists of various cell types of Hydroid. <ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q3332857}}\n\n[[Category:Anthomedusae]]\n[[Category:Animals described in 1993]]\n\n\n{{Cnidarian-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n| taxon = Bougainvillia aberrans\n| authority = Calder, 1993\n}}\n\n'''''Bougainvillia aberrans''''' is a marine [[invertebrate]], a [[species]] of [[hydroid (zoology)|hydroid]] in the suborder [[Anthomedusae]].<ref name=\":0\">Calder, D. R. (1993). Bougainvillia aberrans (Cnidaria, Hydrozoa), a new species of hydroid and medusa from the upper bathyal zone off Bermuda. ''Canadian Journal of Zoology'', ''71''(5), 997\u20131002. doi: 10.1139/z93-132</ref> It was first described by Dale Calder in 1993.<ref>{{cite WoRMS |author=Peter Schuchert |year=2010 |title=''Bougainvillia aberrans'' Calder, 1993 |db=Hydrozoa |id=284227 |accessdate=June 26, 2012}}</ref> They have four radical clusters of marginal [[Tentacle|tentacles]]. <ref>''Bougainvillia Sp. - Guide to the Marine Zooplankton of South Eastern Australia'', web.archive.org/web/20120322022902/http:/www.tafi.org.au/zooplankton/imagekey/cnidaria/hydrozoa/hydroidomedusae/anthomedusae/bougainvillia.html.</ref> ''Bougainvillia aberrans'' is found in [[Bermuda]] in the western [[North Atlantic Ocean]]. <ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Description ==\n''Bougainvillia aberrans'' consists of the [[hydroid]] colony with soft curly [[perisarc]] polysiphonic hydrocaulus, hydranths <ref name=\":0\" /> including 16 tentacles maximum, and medusa buds. Hydroid is part of the Cnidaria phylum. <ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=Castro, Peter,|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/1085562213|title=Marine biology|others=Huber, Michael E.,, Ober, William C.,, Ober, Claire E.,|isbn=1-260-08510-4|edition=Eleventh edition|location=New York, NY|oclc=1085562213}}</ref> So, ''B. aberrans'' are radial symmetry, that they have [[Cnidaria|cnidae]] that are unique sting structures unique to this phylum. <ref name=\":2\" /> ''Bougainvillia aberrans'' is different from other [[Hydrant|hydranths]] species because ''B. abberans'' have a lengthy spindled manubrium, negligible tentacles, and survive for a short period. In the sense that different from other with known species in all. <ref name=\":0\" />This species is characterized as comparatively large size, about 20 mm width as well as height, and large amounts of folded hanging [[Gonad|gonads]] from the wall around the circumference to the proximal area of the radial canals. <ref name=\":1\" /> Also, Cnidoma of ''Bougainivillia'' is similar to the genus of other species, the edge tentacles have extinct species, and the oral tentacles have anti-inflammatory properties. <ref name=\":1\">Nogueira, M., Rodriguez, C. S., Mianzan, H., Haddad, M. A., & Genzano, G. (2013). Description of a new hydromedusa from the southwestern Atlantic Ocean,Bougainvillia pagesisp. nov. (Cnidaria, Hydrozoa, Anthoathecata). ''Marine Ecology'', ''34'', 113\u2013122. doi: 10.1111/maec.12030</ref> \n\n<br />\n\n== Distribution and habitat ==\nHydroid species ''Bougainvillia aberrans'' distribute from shallow water to deep sea in the Bermuda area. <ref>Calder, D. R. (1998). Hydroid diversity and species composition along a gradient from shallow waters to deep sea around Bermuda. ''Deep Sea Research Part I: Oceanographic Research Papers'', ''45''(11), 1843\u20131860. doi: 10.1016/s0967-0637(98)00044-2</ref> Members of the genus are found in all seas, but most of the known species are found in the [[Atlantic Ocean]]. In the western [[North Atlantic ocean|North Atlantic Ocean]], the [[polypropylene]] buoy line in the crab-catching trap, located 2.5 kilometers southeast of Castle Roads, was collected with a depth of 311 meters, which was found to be growing about 37 meters from the floor. <ref name=\":0\" />\n<br />\n\n== Biology ==\nHydroid colonies arise or stand upright due to creeping hydrorhiza .Monosiphonic or polysiphonic hydrocaulus are companions of erect colonies. <ref name=\":0\" /> ''Bougainvillia aberrans'' is distinguishable in the sense that the degree of reduction of its medusa is unique compared to species of same genus. Moreover, ''B. aberrans'' is suppressed in the medusa stage. Hydroids of ''B. aberrans'' feed on fragments of other cnidarians. <ref name=\":2\" /> Cnidaria have a centered mouth surrounded by tentacles. Also, the they are carnivorous. <ref name=\":2\" /> In terms of reproduction, gametes were released before or shortly after the release of the mediating from the hydroid. ''Bougainvillia aberrans n. sp''. has [[holotype]] and [[paratype]]. Also, medusae ''of B. aberrans'' appear sexually mature and relatively short-lived for release from the hydroid. It is different from the reduced Medusa buds with its blunt marginal tentacles. Furthermore, the perisarc of ''B. aberrans'' is clear and not covered with mud or sand. The latest ''B. aberrans'' eggs are surrounded by envelopes with tiny heterotrchous microbasic eurytele [[Nematocyst (dinoflagellate)|nematocysts]]. <ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q3332857}}\n\n[[Category:Anthomedusae]]\n[[Category:Animals described in 1993]]\n\n\n{{Cnidarian-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Hscbu0907", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bougainvillia_aberrans"}
{"title_page": "Never Seen the Rain", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Never Seen the Rain\n| cover      = Never Seen the Rain by Tones and I.png\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Tones and I]]\n| EP         = [[The Kids Are Coming]]\n| released   = {{start date|2019|07|16|df=yes}}\n| format     = {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[Streaming media|streaming]]}}\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = \n| length     = {{Duration|m=3|s=20}}\n| label      = Bad Batch\n| writer     =\n| producer   = [[Konstantin Kersting]]\n| prev_title = [[Dance Monkey]]\n| prev_year  = 2019\n| next_title = [[The Kids Are Coming (song)|The Kids Are Coming]]\n| next_year  = 2019\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|UdRJY-jlEhQ|\"Never Seen the Rain\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Never Seen the Rain'''\" is a song by Australian singer [[Tones and I]], released in Australia on 16 July 2019 as the third single (second in the US) from Tones and I's debut EP ''[[The Kids Are Coming]]''. Upon release Tones and I said \"[It's] about people who live the same repetitive life in fear of failure. So, they never try.\"<ref name=\"FirstSpin\">{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/triplej/news/musicnews/tones-and-i-new-song-never-seen-rain-debut-ep-kids-are-coming/11312586|title=First Spin: Tones And I continues winning streak with 'Never Seen The Rain'|publisher=ABC|date=16 July 2019 |accessdate=18 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://musicfeeds.com.au/news/listen-to-a-new-song-from-tones-and-i-never-seen-the-rain/|title= Listen To A New Song From Tones And I, \u2018Never Seen The Rain\u2019|publisher=Music Feeds|date=16 July 2019|accessdate=20 July 2019}}</ref> \nIn January 2020, the single was released outside of Australia. In February, it achieved gold status in New Zealand.\n\n==Critical reception==\nAl Newstead from ABC said \"'Never Seen the Rain' retains her keen pop sensibilities but wraps those distinctive vocals into an uplifting chorus.\"<ref name=\"FirstSpin\"/>\n\n==Music video==\nThe music video was produced by Visible Studios, directed by Nick Kozakis and Liam Kelly, and released on 7 August 2019.\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits adapted from [[AllMusic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/never-seen-the-rain-mw0003309292/credits|title=Never Seen The Rain - Tones and I|publisher=AllMusic|accessdate=16 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n* [[Tones and I|Toni Watson]] \u2013 composer\n* [[Konstantin Kersting]] \u2013 mixing, production\n* Andrei Eremin \u2013 mastering\n\n==Charts==\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2019\u20132020)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{single chart|Australia|7|artist=Tones and I|song=Never Seen the Rain|rowheader=true|accessdate=8 January 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Austria|70|artist=Tones and I|song=Never Seen the Rain|rowheader=true|accessdate=2 April 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Flanders|7|artist=Tones and I|song=Never Seen the Rain|rowheader=true|accessdate=14 March 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Wallonia|4|artist=Tones and I|song=Never Seen the Rain|rowheader=true|accessdate=10 April 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| France ([[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|SNEP]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://snepmusique.com/les-tops/le-top-de-la-semaine/top-albums/?semaine=15?&annee=2020&categorie=Top%20Singles|title=Top Singles (Week 15, 2020)|publisher=[[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique]]|language=French|accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n| 46\n|-\n{{single chart|Germany2|51|songid=1893470|artist=Tones and I|song=Never Seen the Rain|rowheader=true|accessdate=3 April 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Ireland ([[Irish Recorded Music Association|IRMA]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://irma.ie/index.cfm?page=irish-charts&chart=Singles|title=IRMA \u2013 Irish Charts|publisher=[[Irish Recorded Music Association]]|accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n| 21\n|-\n! scope